english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord Lee, Former Counselor-in-Waiting and Minister of the Palace, with Preface
  author: Lee Gyeobbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lord Lee's given name was Sehwa and his courtesy name was Geosil. His native place was Jinju. His father, whose name was [not given], held the rank of Inspector General. His mother was the Lady of Haeyang, of the Kim clan, daughter of [an official whose name was not given]. When the Lord was young, though his father was a military official, knowing that his nature was brilliant and perceptive, he would surely achieve distinction through learning. Thus he had him study early, and the Lord applied himself diligently to learning and became skilled in composition. In the spring of the year Muoja, he took the Sunggyun examination and passed. In the year Imsuil, he took the civil service examination and was selected with a rank of bingjae. During the reign of Jeongmyo, he was registered in the Tea Chamber, but was soon dismissed for official reasons. Later he was again registered among the palace attendants. When Kangmyo passed away, he was dismissed according to precedent. Though the Lord had not served as a provincial official, he was appointed to a salaried position as Inspector of Gyeonnju. In the year Byungja he was transferred to the position of Bureau Chief of the Metropolitan Military Administration. In the autumn of Jeongchuk he went out to serve as Commander of the Jeongryong District. He was highly regarded by General Zhao, the commander-in-chief. When he was recalled, the General submitted a memorial requesting that he remain on his staff and entrusted him with important matters. When the General returned to court, he strongly recommended him for promotion to Vice-Director of the Great Granary. In the spring of Gyeongsin he went out as Commander of the Baekryeong Fort. He administered the county with integrity and impartiality. This county had previously lacked a local school, and the Lord was the first to establish one. He gathered the children of officials and commoners and taught them learning. Within a few years, all had become talented individuals, and some even presented themselves for the civil service examination. The whole county admired him, and repeatedly submitted documents praising him. When his term ended, he was appointed Bureau Chief of the Ssinho Guard. Soon after he also held concurrently the position of Chief of the Metropolitan Military Administration, and through successive appointments eventually became Director of the Inner Garden Bureau and Court Gentleman. In the summer of Gapsin he was promoted to Recorder of the Department of State Affairs. That winter he was appointed Right Remonstrator and Compiler of Imperial Edicts. Soon after he was promoted to Supervising Censor of the Palace and granted the Purple Fish Bag. Not long after, he was promoted to Right Counselor of Remonstrance and Compiler of Imperial Edicts. In the spring of Jeonghai he went out to govern Nanyuan. The next year he was transferred to govern Dongju. Again his administration was noted as excellent. In the spring of Gyeonggin he was recalled as a Supervising Censor with the Purple Rank. The following autumn he was sent to inspect Gyeongsang Province. It happened that the Mongols made a great incursion into the border. The five provincial inspectors all led troops to render aid. The Lord rushed to organize the military forces and was first among all the provinces to meet the deadline. Moreover, he commanded the troops like a seasoned veteran, and those who heard of it praised him. In the year Imjin he was appointed Vice Minister of Rites and Censor. That summer, as the nation was preparing to relocate the capital due to Mongol invasion, and as Gwangju was a great fortress on the central route, the court deliberated and selected him to go out and defend it. In the eleventh month of winter, the Mongol forces came in great numbers, surrounding the city in scores of layers and attacking with hundreds of stratagems for several months. Day and night the Lord prepared the defenses and responded to circumstances with unexpected tactics, at times capturing and slaying many of the enemy. The Mongols, seeing they could not prevail, lifted their siege and departed. The county lay at a critical junction on the southern route. Had the city fallen, the fate of all the others would have been sealed. Without the Lord, the situation would have been dire. In ages past, when Zhang Xun defended Suiyang, though his integrity and valor were worthy of praise, he could not escape death and the fall of the city. The Lord, however, was able to defend it to the death and transform it into a place of life; ultimately preserving himself, keeping the city intact, and saving ten thousand lives. Thus his merit surpassed that of Zhang Xun. At the time, all thought he would soon receive favor and appointment, yet he remained there for three years. Was this not because the court, recognizing his defensive prowess, hesitated to change its commander? In the winter of Eulmi, he was recalled with the rank of Lord of Dispersed Ranks, Attendant-in-Chief of the Board of Rites, Right Counselor of Remonstrance, Direct Scholar of the Precious Literature Pavilion, and Compiler of Imperial Edicts. This was a reward for his merit. Soon after he was promoted to Attendant-in-Chief of the Board of Personnel, while retaining his position as Counselor of Remonstrance. In the summer of Jeongyu he again went out to defend the mountain fortress of Cheongju. The Mongols, knowing the Lord was skilled in defense, dared not attack. In the winter he was appointed Lord Chancellor and Counselor of State, while retaining his former position. On the Mid-Autumn Festival of the year Museul, at home with his sons and sons-in-law, enjoying the moon and wine in pleasant conversation, he suddenly collapsed while raising his cup and could not rise. By dawn he had passed away. Alas, how strange! Why did he depart so suddenly? The Lord, in character, bore noble dignity and composure with depth and integrity. He first became known to the world through his writing, yet his administrative abilities and strategic mind were equally impressive in all their applications. He was indeed a complete talent. Yet he never became Prime Minister before his passing. Was this not the decree of Heaven? His first wife was the daughter of Vice Minister of Rites Heo Gyeong, but she passed away. He remarried the daughter of General Seol of the Heungwi Guard. He had three sons and six daughters. The eldest son, Soojin, served as Vice-Judge of Nanyuan. Soonyeon is a Clerk of Angyeong. Soosim has not yet come of age. The eldest daughter married the official Liu Jingro. The others married officials [whose names are omitted]. Two daughters are still young. When the funeral rites were being prepared, his son Soonyeon and son-in-law Jingro, having arranged the biographical account, requested of me an epitaph to preserve his memory eternally. As I too had known the Lord, I could not refuse on grounds of propriety. Thus I inscribe this epitaph:

    Guangzhou in the southern land
    Stands as the critical fortress gate,
    Where the sovereign's reliance lay
    As upon a shield for all the realm.

    Then came our Lord,
    Raised to become regional magistrate,
    When barbarians came to lay siege,
    And fate hung in uncertain balance.

    With force of will he held them back,
    With laughter turned the enemy aside,
    His body offered to dispel calamity—
    So bright his deeds shone forth.

    Ten thousand lives he saved from death,
    His hidden virtue echoed through the ages.

    All voices in the realm proclaimed
    He would soon reach the highest post.
    Just half a step remained to climb,
    Yet Heaven would not grant him more.

    Swiftly as morning dew he faded,
    A tangled knot whose cause none can untie.

    Yet brilliant shine his deeds of merit,
    To illuminate the ages yet unborn.

    This humble epitaph I carve
    Is but a feather of the great phoenix.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhang Xun (張巡) was a Tang Dynasty general famous for his desperate defense of Suiyang against the An Lushan Rebellion. He ultimately died in battle after the city fell. The comparison emphasizes that Lee not only defended his position but also survived and preserved both city and people.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'three years' suggests the Lord was so valued by the court that they delayed his promotion, keeping him in place as a fortress commander.
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph employs the classical fu (賦) style, blending narrative with lyrical reflection on the transience of life and the lasting nature of virtue.
